comments: The second half was much more difficult since there was a lack of context to the rest of the conversation. I reread the conversations in my head and for some it sounded as though the statements were true when there was a lack of context.
Sometimes the question was phrased a bit weirdly but it was ok to figure out
The experiment was relatively strait forward and easy to do.

there were two questions that the initial statement and answer to the question make the speaker contradict themselves (the one about the pretending to get a cat and the one with Michelle and Mandy), which made the question hard to answer.
I am an ESL teacher. I'd be curious to see if language teachers answer in similar ways.

Interesting survey! The questions were fairly confusing however
Instructions were a bit confusing in the first part.
It took me a few minutes (sorry) to understand what I was being tasked with so I think some of my early answers in each part were wrong headed.

The thing is that depending on context/inflections [I am not a linguist] there are multiple ways of "reading" the majority of these statements. If the speaker was issuing a retort, semantically, the statements could be read in a different way than if the speaker was relaying positive information. The fact that different words have varying significances in the study's characteristic formulation [per A, not X] is often overwhelmed by this "flatness" of the dialogue which can be subject to multiple readings.
I can't think of anything; this was a really interesting experiment.

This was very interesting, after a while (in the second part of the task) I found myself wondering if maybe x DID answer y's question, when for the first few I was certain.  Very interesting - thanks for the opportunity to participate!
